Robdeltonie 2023-06-09 8:41 PM
Here's something I would like feedback on. I'm sure like many of you, we would like a studio version of the Cinematic Tour Intro (named "Anthem" on the setlist). Unfortunately, I doubt we will ever get it. So recently, I ripped the audio from this YouTube video with a high-quality version of the intro: https://youtu.be/k8D-lDLq9k4 ...and I set out to remaster it. I used AI music separation tools to separate the cheers and applause as best as I could from the actual music. I then used Audacity to try to level the music when the cheers were removed. I also added the raw samples from Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory back in and applied effects close enough to match the original, as that was also removed when I removed the cheers. I did some more work in Audacity, did a stem remastering based on AI-separated stems from the studio version of Verge, and I finished the remaster in Logic. In Logic, I mostly used EQ and compression, but I also made the main track mono and added a stereo widener to fix some strange distortion/filtering going on in the raw stereo image. And I also added automation to the volume to add some dynamic range back to the track instead of sounding smooshed and loud throughout the whole track. And this was the result. I would like to hear your thoughts on this version. I'm personally satisfied with it, but I'm still learning audio production in terms of music. So any feedback would be appreciated. Also note this is just the intro, not a live version of Verge or the outro at the end that mirrored the intro. Please let me know what you think!
VoyagerRick
Owl City - Verge (Cinematic Tour intro) (Live)

Robdeltonie
Here's something I would like feedback on. I'm sure like many of you, we would like a studio version of the Cinematic Tour Intro (named "Anthem" on the setlist). Unfortunately, I doubt we will ever get it. So recently, I ripped the audio from this YouTube video with a high-quality version of the intro: https://youtu.be/k8D-lDLq9k4 ...and I set out to remaster it. I used AI music separation tools to separate the cheers and applause as best as I could from the actual music. I then used Audacity to try to level the music when the cheers were removed. I also added the raw samples from Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory back in and applied effects close enough to match the original, as that was also removed when I removed the cheers. I did some more work in Audacity, did a stem remastering based on AI-separated stems from the studio version of Verge, and I finished the remaster in Logic. In Logic, I mostly used EQ and compression, but I also made the main track mono and added a stereo widener to fix some strange distortion/filtering going on in the raw stereo image. And I also added automation to the volume to add some dynamic range back to the track instead of sounding smooshed and loud throughout the whole track. And this was the result. I would like to hear your thoughts on this version. I'm personally satisfied with it, but I'm still learning audio production in terms of music. So any feedback would be appreciated. Also note this is just the intro, not a live version of Verge or the outro at the end that mirrored the intro. Please let me know what you think!

Q_us
Hey i went through some tutorials and tried following it to the best of my ability for my unique mix and was wondering if there was anything else i could do that i didnt do here? (basically, for someone whoâ€™s never mastered a song before, is this the right idea )
M a n B i r d â„¢ 2023-07-24 9:02 PM
the biggest thing mastering does is looking at dynamics and volume compared to like other tracks. theres ofc also the thing of looking at frequencies and making sure that for example your bass isnt way too loud compared to the rest but the volume part is probably what most ppl are concerned with especially when doing it themselves. your file is still veeeeery dynamic to the point where most listeners probably would have to adjust their volume if they listen to this after some other song, then as the intensity goes up they most likely will have to adjust it again as its getting really loud
9:04 PM
theres nothing wrong with a dynamic master, i for one am a big fan of more dynamics and keeping things more natural compared to the overcompressed and crushed things that resulted from the whole loudness wars and ppl trying to just squash everything, but theres a middle ground to be found there
9:07 PM
example, Yours it at the top, the middle one is one of my songs and the bottom one is tornado to just see how that compares and since i feel like thats quite a dynamic song. you can see how at the start and after the first really loud part, yours gets really quiet. you could try and bring those peaks and valleys together slightly. theres no right or wrong way to do that and theres no need to do that fully when mastering. you could use some automation on individual channels in the mix or try stuff on a whole bus before going to the master. Its a very deep rabbit hole and theres loads to be learned, as long as you keep going you ll find stuff that suits your workflow
9:07 PM
(sorry for that whole encyclopedia of text lol, im trynna help haha)
Deleted User
More confident than I was. Iâ€™d say my voice has become stronger too
M a n B i r d â„¢ 2023-07-24 9:44 PM
thats the thing with most singing, dont hold back, try to relax le muslces as much as you can and go ham lol. im not one to talk about technique tho (river you there? haha) but just doing helped me greatly. also dont force stuff and if stuff hurts dont push further
1

Its a very deep rabbit hole and theres loads to be learned, as long as you keep going you ll find stuff that suits your workflow
